Escape

by: Aditya Khandelwal

This game was made for my level 2 project at The League of Amazing Programmers.
Click here to download and play!

1. Why I Made This Game

I decided to make this game because I wanted to make a game that was similar to a platformer. I tried making a platformer game before but it didn't work so I decided to try it again to see if I could make it work this time.

2. What I Learned

I learned in user testing that my game was too button-heavy and that clicking all those buttons took some time, so to fix that I replaced some of the buttons with keys so that it took less time to switch between screens. Another change was that some people preferred to play the game with WASD rather than the arrow keys, so I made it so that the player can be controlled with both WASD and arrow keys. The last change I made was that the player could fall forever if they fell off the platform in certain spots so I fixed the lapses in coverage so that the player would die if falling off the platform in all spots.

3. Architecture of My Game

The main parts of my game are the player character, the platform, and the spike. The player tries to maneuver the character to the end of the level while trying not to fall off the platform and trying to avoid the spikes. If the player character class interacts with the spike class, it stops the player from moving through the platform. If the player character class interacts with the spike class, the number of lives left for the player decreases by one. When there are zero lives left, the game is over.

4. Technical Implementation

One aspect of the game that I am proud of is the collisions part of the game. At first, there were a lot of problems when the player and the platform collided with each other. The player wouldn't be able to move when touching a platform, would get stuck in the platform, and sometimes would just hover above it and not be able to touch it. But by fixing and tweaking how the collision worked and implementing some new methods into the game, the player and platform collision started working great.

5. Most Challenging Part

The most challenging part of this project was getting the player character's movement and gravity to work. The player kept getting stuck in the platform when it moved in two directions at once. For example if it was moving down and right at the same time, it would get stuck in the corner of the platform and then would not be able to move because the player and platform collision statement would not let it move.

6. Future Fixes and Updates

One thing that I would add to the game in the future is an enemy class that would be able to shoot projectiles at the player character. The player character would also have its own gun that could be used to get rid of the enemies while also dodging their bullets.
